{"key":"processedPost-12300659","value":{"id":12300659,"first":12300597,"last":12300659,"when":1269989712,"utime":"03/31/10 01:55 AM","cleanedPost":"First of all, hydrometers measure the specific gravity of liquids.&nbsp; There is no use for one in mycology.<br />In addition, while 100% humidity is fine, it's worthless without massive air exchange.&nbsp; Fresh air is the pinning trigger you want, not saturation humidity.&nbsp; Your idea of a paper towel test won't tell anything.&nbsp; If you want a terrarium for fruiting small bulk substrates, build a shotgun terrarium.&nbsp; It's about the best way to go if you don't have a hygrometer.&nbsp; If you build it <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Terrarium-Tek\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">per the tek,</a> your humidity will be correct.<br />RR"}}